# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: semiconductor-materials
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:semiconductor-materials/band-gap] In solid-state physics and solid-state chemistry, a **band gap**, also called a **bandgap** or **energy gap**, is an energy range in a solid where no electronic states exist.
[src:semiconductor-materials/band-gap] In graphs of the electronic band structure of solids, the band gap refers to the energy difference (often expressed in electronvolts) between the top of the valence band and the bottom of the conduction band in insulators and semiconductors.
[src:semiconductor-materials/band-gap] It is the energy required to promote an electron from the valence band to the conduction band.
[src:semiconductor-materials/band-gap] The resulting conduction-band electron (and the electron hole in the valence band) are free to move within the crystal lattice and serve as charge carriers to conduct electric current.
[src:semiconductor-materials/band-gap] It is closely related to the HOMO–LUMO gap in chemistry.
[src:semiconductor-materials/band-gap] If the valence band is completely full and the conduction band is completely empty, then electrons cannot move within the solid because there are no available states.
[src:semiconductor-materials/band-gap] If the electrons are not free to move within the crystal lattice, then there is no generated current due to no net charge carrier mobility.
[src:semiconductor-materials/band-gap] However, if some electrons transfer from the valence band (mostly full) to the conduction band (mostly empty), then current *can* flow (see carrier generation and recombination).
[src:semiconductor-materials/band-gap] Therefore, the band gap is a major factor determining the electrical conductivity of a solid.
[src:semiconductor-materials/band-gap] It is possible to produce laser induced insulator-metal transitions which have already been experimentally observed in some condensed matter systems, like thin films of C60, doped manganites, or in vanadium sesquioxide V2O3.
[src:semiconductor-materials/band-gap] These are special cases of the more general metal-to-nonmetal transitions phenomena which were intensively studied in the last decades.
[src:semiconductor-materials/band-gap] A one-dimensional analytic model of laser induced distortion of band structure was presented for a spatially periodic (cosine) potential.
[src:semiconductor-materials/band-gap] This problem is periodic both in space and time and can be solved analytically using the Kramers-Henneberger co-moving frame.
[src:semiconductor-materials/band-gap] The solutions can be given with the help of the Mathieu functions.
[src:semiconductor-materials/band-gap] Every solid has its own characteristic energy-band structure.
[src:semiconductor-materials/band-gap] This variation in band structure is responsible for the wide range of electrical characteristics observed in various materials.
[src:semiconductor-materials/band-gap] Depending on the dimension, the band structure and spectroscopy can vary.
[src:semiconductor-materials/band-gap] The different types of dimensions are as listed: one dimension, two dimensions, and three dimensions.
[src:semiconductor-materials/band-gap] In semiconductors and insulators, electrons are confined to a number of bands of energy, and forbidden from other regions because there are no allowable electronic states for them to occupy.
[src:semiconductor-materials/band-gap] The term "band gap" refers to the energy difference between the top of the valence band and the bottom of the conduction band.
[src:semiconductor-materials/band-gap] Electrons are able to jump from one band to another.
[src:semiconductor-materials/band-gap] However, in order for a valence band electron to be promoted to the conduction band, it requires a specific minimum amount of energy for the transition.
[src:semiconductor-materials/band-gap] This required energy is an intrinsic characteristic of the solid material.
[src:semiconductor-materials/band-gap] Electrons can gain enough energy to jump to the conduction band by absorbing either a phonon (heat) or a photon (light).
[src:semiconductor-materials/band-gap] A semiconductor is a material with an intermediate-sized, non-zero band gap that behaves as an insulator at T=0K, but allows thermal excitation of electrons into its conduction band at temperatures that are below its melting point.
[src:semiconductor-materials/band-gap] In contrast, a material with a large band gap is an insulator.
[src:semiconductor-materials/band-gap] In conductors, the valence and conduction bands may overlap, so there is no longer a bandgap with forbidden regions of electronic states.
[src:semiconductor-materials/band-gap] The conductivity of intrinsic semiconductors is strongly dependent on the band gap.
[src:semiconductor-materials/band-gap] The only available charge carriers for conduction are the electrons that have enough thermal energy to be excited across the band gap and the electron holes that are left off when such an excitation occurs.
[src:semiconductor-materials/band-gap] Band-gap engineering is the process of controlling or altering the band gap of a material by controlling the composition of certain semiconductor alloys, such as GaAlAs, InGaAs, and InAlAs.
[src:semiconductor-materials/band-gap] It is also possible to construct layered materials with alternating compositions by techniques like molecular-beam epitaxy.
[src:semiconductor-materials/band-gap] These methods are exploited in the design of heterojunction bipolar transistors (HBTs), laser diodes and solar cells.
[src:semiconductor-materials/band-gap] The distinction between semiconductors and insulators is a matter of convention.
[src:semiconductor-materials/band-gap] One approach is to think of semiconductors as a type of insulator with a narrow band gap.
[src:semiconductor-materials/band-gap] Insulators with a larger band gap, usually greater than 4 eV, are not considered semiconductors and generally do not exhibit semiconductive behaviour under practical conditions.
[src:semiconductor-materials/band-gap] Electron mobility also plays a role in determining a material's informal classification.
[src:semiconductor-materials/band-gap] The band-gap energy of semiconductors tends to decrease with increasing temperature.
[src:semiconductor-materials/band-gap] When temperature increases, the amplitude of atomic vibrations increase, leading to larger interatomic spacing.
[src:semiconductor-materials/band-gap] The interaction between the lattice phonons and the free electrons and holes will also affect the band gap to a smaller extent.
[src:semiconductor-materials/band-gap] The relationship between band gap energy and temperature can be described by Varshni's empirical expression (named after Y.
[src:semiconductor-materials/band-gap] Furthermore, lattice vibrations increase with temperature, which increases the effect of electron scattering.
[src:semiconductor-materials/band-gap] Additionally, the number of charge carriers within a semiconductor will increase, as more carriers have the energy required to cross the band-gap threshold and so conductivity of semiconductors also increases with increasing temperature.
[src:semiconductor-materials/band-gap] The external pressure also influences the electronic structure of semiconductors and, therefore, their optical band gaps.
[src:semiconductor-materials/band-gap] In a regular semiconductor crystal, the band gap is fixed owing to continuous energy states.
[src:semiconductor-materials/band-gap] In a quantum dot crystal, energy states are discretized due to the quantum confinement effect.
[src:semiconductor-materials/band-gap] Energy states in the conduction band are pushed upwards in energy, while those in the valence band are pushed downwards, causing the effective band gap to grow with decreasing dot size.
[src:semiconductor-materials/band-gap] Band gaps can be either direct or indirect, depending on the electronic band structure of the material.
[src:semiconductor-materials/band-gap] It was mentioned earlier that the dimensions have different band structure and spectroscopy.
[src:semiconductor-materials/band-gap] For non-metallic solids, which are one dimensional, have optical properties that are dependent on the electronic transitions between valence and conduction bands.
[src:semiconductor-materials/band-gap] In addition, the spectroscopic transition probability is between the initial and final orbital and it depends on the integral. φi is the initial orbital, φf is the final orbital, ʃ φf*ûεφi is the integral, ε is the electric vector, and u is the dipole moment.
[src:semiconductor-materials/band-gap] Two-dimensional structures of solids behave because of the overlap of atomic orbitals.
[src:semiconductor-materials/band-gap] The simplest two-dimensional crystal contains identical atoms arranged on a square lattice.
[src:semiconductor-materials/band-gap] Energy splitting occurs at the Brillouin zone edge for one-dimensional situations because of a weak periodic potential, which produces a gap between bands.
[src:semiconductor-materials/band-gap] The behavior of the one-dimensional situations does not occur for two-dimensional cases because there are extra freedoms of motion.
[src:semiconductor-materials/band-gap] Furthermore, a bandgap can be produced with strong periodic potential for two-dimensional and three-dimensional cases.
[src:semiconductor-materials/band-gap] Based on their band structure, materials are characterised with a direct band gap or indirect band gap.
[src:semiconductor-materials/band-gap] In the free-electron model, k is the momentum of a free electron and assumes unique values within the Brillouin zone that outlines the periodicity of the crystal lattice.
[src:semiconductor-materials/band-gap] If the momentum of the lowest energy state in the conduction band and the highest energy state of the valence band of a material have the same value, then the material has a direct bandgap.
[src:semiconductor-materials/band-gap] If they are not the same, then the material has an indirect band gap and the electronic transition must undergo momentum transfer to satisfy conservation.
[src:semiconductor-materials/band-gap] Such indirect "forbidden" transitions still occur, however at very low probabilities and weaker energy.
[src:semiconductor-materials/band-gap] For materials with a direct band gap, valence electrons can be directly excited into the conduction band by a photon whose energy is larger than the bandgap.
[src:semiconductor-materials/band-gap] In contrast, for materials with an indirect band gap, a photon and phonon must both be involved in a transition from the valence band top to the conduction band bottom, involving a momentum change.
[src:semiconductor-materials/band-gap] LEDs and laser diodes usually emit photons with energy close to and slightly larger than the band gap of the semiconductor material from which they are made.
[src:semiconductor-materials/band-gap] Therefore, as the band gap energy increases, the LED or laser color changes from infrared to red, through the rainbow to violet, then to UV.
[src:semiconductor-materials/band-gap] The optical band gap determines what portion of the solar spectrum a photovoltaic cell absorbs.
[src:semiconductor-materials/band-gap] Strictly, a semiconductor will not absorb photons of energy less than the band gap; whereas most of the photons with energies exceeding the band gap will generate heat.
[src:semiconductor-materials/band-gap] Neither of them contribute to the efficiency of a solar cell.
[src:semiconductor-materials/band-gap] Below are band gap values for some selected materials.
[src:semiconductor-materials/band-gap] For a comprehensive list of band gaps in semiconductors, see List of semiconductor materials.
[src:semiconductor-materials/band-gap] It is possible for an absorbed photon to have just enough energy to generate a bound electron–hole pair (an exciton), but not enough additional energy to separate the two against their mutual electrical attraction.
[src:semiconductor-materials/band-gap] The former energy is called the "optical band gap", while the energy to create an unbound pair so that a macroscopic electrical current will flow is the "electronic band gap" or "transport gap", and is greater than the former by the exciton binding energy.
[src:semiconductor-materials/band-gap] In almost all inorganic semiconductors (silicon, gallium arsenide, etc.) there is very little interaction between electrons and holes, thus the exciton binding energy is very low, and the difference between the two gaps is usually ignored.
[src:semiconductor-materials/band-gap] However, in some systems, including organic semiconductors and single-walled carbon nanotubes, the distinction may be significant.
[src:semiconductor-materials/band-gap] In photonics, band gaps or stop bands are ranges of photon frequencies where, if tunneling effects are neglected, no photons can be transmitted through a material.
[src:semiconductor-materials/band-gap] A material exhibiting this behaviour is known as a photonic crystal.
[src:semiconductor-materials/band-gap] The concept of hyperuniformity has broadened the range of photonic band gap materials, beyond photonic crystals.
[src:semiconductor-materials/band-gap] By applying the technique in supersymmetric quantum mechanics, a new class of optical disordered materials has been suggested, which support band gaps perfectly equivalent to those of crystals or quasicrystals.
[src:semiconductor-materials/band-gap] Similar physics applies to phonons in a phononic crystal.
[src:semiconductor-materials/charge-carrier] In solid state physics, a **charge carrier** is a particle or quasiparticle that is free to move, carrying an electric charge, especially the particles that carry electric charges in electrical conductors.
[src:semiconductor-materials/charge-carrier] In a conducting medium, an electric field can exert force on these free particles, causing a net motion of the particles through the medium; this is what constitutes an electric current.
[src:semiconductor-materials/charge-carrier] The electron and the proton are the **elementary charge carriers**, each carrying one elementary charge (*e*), of the same magnitude and opposite sign.
[src:semiconductor-materials/charge-carrier] In conducting mediums, particles serve to carry charge.
[src:semiconductor-materials/charge-carrier] In many metals, the charge carriers are electrons.
[src:semiconductor-materials/charge-carrier] One or two of the valence electrons from each atom are able to move about freely within the crystal structure of the metal.
[src:semiconductor-materials/charge-carrier] The free electrons are referred to as conduction electrons, and the cloud of free electrons is called a Fermi gas.
[src:semiconductor-materials/charge-carrier] Many metals have electron and hole bands.
[src:semiconductor-materials/charge-carrier] In some, the majority carriers are holes.
[src:semiconductor-materials/charge-carrier] In electrolytes, such as salt water, the charge carriers are ions, which are atoms or molecules that have gained or lost electrons so they are electrically charged.
[src:semiconductor-materials/charge-carrier] Atoms that have gained electrons so they are negatively charged are called anions, atoms that have lost electrons so they are positively charged are called cations.
[src:semiconductor-materials/charge-carrier] Cations and anions of the dissociated liquid also serve as charge carriers in melted ionic solids (see e.g. the Hall–Héroult process for an example of electrolysis of a melted ionic solid).
[src:semiconductor-materials/charge-carrier] Proton conductors are electrolytic conductors employing positive hydrogen ions as carriers.
[src:semiconductor-materials/charge-carrier] In a plasma, an electrically charged gas which is found in electric arcs through air, neon signs, and the sun and stars, the electrons and cations of ionized gas act as charge carriers.
[src:semiconductor-materials/charge-carrier] In a vacuum, free electrons can act as charge carriers.
[src:semiconductor-materials/charge-carrier] In the electronic component known as the vacuum tube (also called *valve*), the mobile electron cloud is generated by a heated metal cathode, by a process called thermionic emission.
[src:semiconductor-materials/charge-carrier] When an electric field is applied strongly enough to draw the electrons into a beam, this may be referred to as a cathode ray, and is the basis of the cathode-ray tube display widely used in televisions and computer monitors until the 2000s.
[src:semiconductor-materials/charge-carrier] In semiconductors, which are the materials used to make electronic components like transistors and integrated circuits, two types of charge carrier are possible.
[src:semiconductor-materials/charge-carrier] In p-type semiconductors, "effective particles" known as electron holes with positive charge move through the crystal lattice, producing an electric current.
[src:semiconductor-materials/charge-carrier] The "holes" are, in effect, electron vacancies in the valence-band electron population of the semiconductor and are treated as charge carriers because they are mobile, moving from atom site to atom site.
[src:semiconductor-materials/charge-carrier] In n-type semiconductors, electrons in the conduction band move through the crystal, resulting in an electric current.
[src:semiconductor-materials/charge-carrier] In some conductors, such as ionic solutions and plasmas, positive and negative charge carriers coexist, so in these cases an electric current consists of the two types of carrier moving in opposite directions.
[src:semiconductor-materials/charge-carrier] In other conductors, such as metals, there are only charge carriers of one polarity, so an electric current in them simply consists of charge carriers moving in one direction.
[src:semiconductor-materials/charge-carrier] There are two recognized types of charge carriers in semiconductors.
[src:semiconductor-materials/charge-carrier] One is electrons, which carry a negative electric charge.
[src:semiconductor-materials/charge-carrier] In addition, it is convenient to treat the traveling vacancies in the valence band electron population (holes) as a second type of charge carrier, which carry a positive charge equal in magnitude to that of an electron.
[src:semiconductor-materials/charge-carrier] When an electron meets with a hole, they recombine and these free carriers effectively vanish.
[src:semiconductor-materials/charge-carrier] The energy released can be either thermal, heating up the semiconductor (*thermal recombination*, one of the sources of waste heat in semiconductors), or released as photons (*optical recombination*, used in LEDs and semiconductor lasers).
[src:semiconductor-materials/charge-carrier] The recombination means an electron which has been excited from the valence band to the conduction band falls back to the empty state in the valence band, known as the holes.
[src:semiconductor-materials/charge-carrier] The holes are the empty states created in the valence band when an electron gets excited after getting some energy to pass the energy gap.
[src:semiconductor-materials/charge-carrier] The more abundant charge carriers are called **majority carriers**, which are primarily responsible for current transport in a piece of semiconductor.
[src:semiconductor-materials/charge-carrier] In n-type semiconductors they are electrons, while in p-type semiconductors they are holes.
[src:semiconductor-materials/charge-carrier] The less abundant charge carriers are called **minority carriers**; in n-type semiconductors they are holes, while in p-type semiconductors they are electrons.
[src:semiconductor-materials/charge-carrier] The concentration of holes and electrons in a doped semiconductor is governed by the mass action law.
[src:semiconductor-materials/charge-carrier] In an intrinsic semiconductor, which does not contain any impurity, the concentrations of both types of carriers are ideally equal.
[src:semiconductor-materials/charge-carrier] If an intrinsic semiconductor is doped with a donor impurity then the majority carriers are electrons.
[src:semiconductor-materials/charge-carrier] If the semiconductor is doped with an acceptor impurity then the majority carriers are holes.
[src:semiconductor-materials/charge-carrier] Minority carriers play an important role in bipolar transistors and solar cells.
[src:semiconductor-materials/charge-carrier] Their role in field-effect transistors (FETs) is a bit more complex: for example, a MOSFET has p-type and n-type regions.
[src:semiconductor-materials/charge-carrier] The transistor action involves the majority carriers of the source and drain regions, but these carriers traverse the body of the opposite type, where they are minority carriers.
[src:semiconductor-materials/charge-carrier] Superconductors have zero electrical resistance and are therefore able to carry current indefinitely.
[src:semiconductor-materials/charge-carrier] This type of conduction is possible by the formation of Cooper pairs.
[src:semiconductor-materials/charge-carrier] At present, superconductors can only be achieved at very low temperatures, for instance by using cryogenic chilling.
[src:semiconductor-materials/charge-carrier] As yet, achieving superconductivity at room temperature remains challenging; it is still a field of ongoing research and experimentation.
[src:semiconductor-materials/charge-carrier] Creating a superconductor that functions at ambient temperature would constitute an important technological break-through, which could potentially contribute to much higher energy efficiency in grid distribution of electricity.
[src:semiconductor-materials/charge-carrier] Under exceptional circumstances, positrons, muons, anti-muons, taus and anti-taus may potentially also carry electric charge.
[src:semiconductor-materials/charge-carrier] This is theoretically possible, yet the very short life-time of these charged particles would render such a current very challenging to maintain at the current state of technology.
[src:semiconductor-materials/charge-carrier] It might be possible to artificially create this type of current, or it might occur in nature during very short lapses of time.
[src:semiconductor-materials/charge-carrier] Electric charge can cause the formation of electromagnetic fields in plasmas, which can lead to the formation of currents or even multiple currents.
[src:semiconductor-materials/charge-carrier] This phenomenon is used in nuclear fusion reactors.
[src:semiconductor-materials/charge-carrier] It also occurs naturally in the cosmos, in the form of jets, nebula winds or cosmic filaments that carry charged particles.
[src:semiconductor-materials/charge-carrier] This cosmic phenomenon is called Birkeland current.
[src:semiconductor-materials/charge-carrier] Considered in general, the electric conductivity of plasmas is a subject of plasma physics.
[src:semiconductor-materials/doping-semiconductor] In semiconductor production, **doping** is the intentional introduction of impurities into an intrinsic (undoped) semiconductor for the purpose of modulating its electrical, optical and structural properties.
[src:semiconductor-materials/doping-semiconductor] The doped material is referred to as an extrinsic semiconductor.
[src:semiconductor-materials/doping-semiconductor] Small numbers of dopant atoms can change the ability of a semiconductor to conduct electricity.
[src:semiconductor-materials/doping-semiconductor] When on the order of one dopant atom is added per 100 million intrinsic atoms, the doping is said to be *low* or *light*.
[src:semiconductor-materials/doping-semiconductor] When many more dopant atoms are added, on the order of one per ten thousand atoms, the doping is referred to as *high* or *heavy*.
[src:semiconductor-materials/doping-semiconductor] This is often shown as *n+* for n-type doping or *p+* for p-type doping.
[src:semiconductor-materials/doping-semiconductor] (*See the article on semiconductors for a more detailed description of the doping mechanism.*) A semiconductor doped to such high levels that it acts more like a conductor than a semiconductor is referred to as a degenerate semiconductor.
[src:semiconductor-materials/doping-semiconductor] A semiconductor can be considered i-type semiconductor if it has been doped in equal quantities of p and n.
[src:semiconductor-materials/doping-semiconductor] In the context of phosphors and scintillators, doping is better known as activation; this is not to be confused with dopant activation in semiconductors.
[src:semiconductor-materials/doping-semiconductor] Doping is also used to control the color in some pigments.
[src:semiconductor-materials/doping-semiconductor] The effects of impurities in semiconductors (doping) were long known empirically in such devices as crystal radio detectors and selenium rectifiers.
[src:semiconductor-materials/doping-semiconductor] For instance, in 1885 Shelford Bidwell, and in 1930 the German scientist Bernhard Gudden, each independently reported that the properties of semiconductors were due to the impurities they contained.
[src:semiconductor-materials/doping-semiconductor] A doping process was formally developed by John Robert Woodyard working at Sperry Gyroscope Company during World War II.
[src:semiconductor-materials/doping-semiconductor] Though the word *doping* is not used in it, his US Patent issued in 1950 describes methods for adding tiny amounts of solid elements from the nitrogen column of the periodic table to germanium to produce rectifying devices.
[src:semiconductor-materials/doping-semiconductor] The demands of his work on radar prevented Woodyard from pursuing further research on semiconductor doping.
[src:semiconductor-materials/doping-semiconductor] Similar work was performed at Bell Labs by Gordon K.
[src:semiconductor-materials/doping-semiconductor] Teal and Morgan Sparks, with a US Patent issued in 1953.
[src:semiconductor-materials/doping-semiconductor] Woodyard's prior patent proved to be the grounds of extensive litigation by Sperry Rand.
[src:semiconductor-materials/doping-semiconductor] The concentration of the dopant used affects many electrical properties of the semi-conductor.
[src:semiconductor-materials/doping-semiconductor] Most important is the material's charge carrier concentration.
[src:semiconductor-materials/doping-semiconductor] In an intrinsic semiconductor under thermal equilibrium, the concentrations of electrons and holes are equivalent.
[src:semiconductor-materials/doping-semiconductor] where *n*0 is the concentration of conducting electrons, *p*0 is the conducting hole concentration, and *ni* is the material's intrinsic carrier concentration.
[src:semiconductor-materials/doping-semiconductor] The intrinsic carrier concentration varies between materials and is dependent on temperature.
[src:semiconductor-materials/doping-semiconductor] Silicon's *ni*, for example, is roughly 1.08×1010 cm−3 at 300 kelvins, about room temperature.
[src:semiconductor-materials/doping-semiconductor] In general, increased doping leads to increased conductivity due to the higher concentration of carriers.
[src:semiconductor-materials/doping-semiconductor] Degenerate (very highly doped) semiconductors have conductivity levels comparable to metals and are often used in integrated circuits as a replacement for metal.
[src:semiconductor-materials/doping-semiconductor] Often superscript plus and minus symbols are used to denote relative doping concentration in semiconductors.
[src:semiconductor-materials/doping-semiconductor] For example, *n*+ denotes an n-type semiconductor with a high, often degenerate, doping concentration.
[src:semiconductor-materials/doping-semiconductor] Similarly, *p*− would indicate a very lightly doped p-type material.
[src:semiconductor-materials/doping-semiconductor] Even degenerate levels of doping imply low concentrations of impurities with respect to the base semiconductor.
[src:semiconductor-materials/doping-semiconductor] In intrinsic crystalline silicon, there are approximately 5×1022 atoms/cm3.
[src:semiconductor-materials/doping-semiconductor] Doping concentration for silicon semiconductors may range anywhere from 1013 cm−3 to 1018 cm−3.
[src:semiconductor-materials/doping-semiconductor] Doping concentration above about 1018 cm−3 is considered degenerate at room temperature.
[src:semiconductor-materials/doping-semiconductor] Degenerately doped silicon contains a proportion of impurity to silicon on the order of parts per thousand.
[src:semiconductor-materials/doping-semiconductor] This proportion may be reduced to parts per billion in very lightly doped silicon.
[src:semiconductor-materials/doping-semiconductor] Typical concentration values fall somewhere in this range and are tailored to produce the desired properties in the device that the semiconductor is intended for.
[src:semiconductor-materials/doping-semiconductor] Doping a semiconductor in a good crystal introduces allowed energy states within the band gap, but very close to the energy band that corresponds to the dopant type.
[src:semiconductor-materials/doping-semiconductor] In other words, electron donor impurities create states near the conduction band while electron acceptor impurities create states near the valence band.
[src:semiconductor-materials/doping-semiconductor] The gap between these energy states and the nearest energy band is usually referred to as dopant-site bonding energy or *EB* and is relatively small.
[src:semiconductor-materials/doping-semiconductor] For example, the *EB* for boron in silicon bulk is 0.045 eV, compared with silicon's band gap of about 1.12 eV.
[src:semiconductor-materials/doping-semiconductor] Because *EB* is so small, room temperature is hot enough to thermally ionize practically all of the dopant atoms and create free charge carriers in the conduction or valence bands.
[src:semiconductor-materials/doping-semiconductor] Dopants also have the important effect of shifting the energy bands relative to the Fermi level.
[src:semiconductor-materials/doping-semiconductor] The energy band that corresponds with the dopant with the greatest concentration ends up closer to the Fermi level.
[src:semiconductor-materials/doping-semiconductor] Since the Fermi level must remain constant in a system in thermodynamic equilibrium, stacking layers of materials with different properties leads to many useful electrical properties induced by band bending, if the interfaces can be made cleanly enough.
[src:semiconductor-materials/doping-semiconductor] For example, the p-n junction's properties are due to the band bending that happens as a result of the necessity to line up the bands in contacting regions of p-type and n-type material.
[src:semiconductor-materials/doping-semiconductor] The band diagram typically indicates the variation in the valence band and conduction band edges versus some spatial dimension, often denoted *x*.
[src:semiconductor-materials/doping-semiconductor] The Fermi level is also usually indicated in the diagram.
[src:semiconductor-materials/doping-semiconductor] Sometimes the *intrinsic Fermi level*, *Ei*, which is the Fermi level in the absence of doping, is shown.
[src:semiconductor-materials/doping-semiconductor] These diagrams are useful in explaining the operation of many kinds of semiconductor devices.
[src:semiconductor-materials/doping-semiconductor] For low levels of doping, the relevant energy states are populated sparsely by electrons (conduction band) or holes (valence band).
[src:semiconductor-materials/doping-semiconductor] where *E*F is the Fermi level, *E*C is the minimum energy of the conduction band, and *E*V is the maximum energy of the valence band.
[src:semiconductor-materials/doping-semiconductor] an expression which is independent of the doping level, since *E*C – *E*V (the band gap) does not change with doping.
[src:semiconductor-materials/doping-semiconductor] where *m**e** and *m**h** are the density of states effective masses of electrons and holes, respectively, quantities that are roughly constant over temperature.
[src:semiconductor-materials/doping-semiconductor] Some dopants are added as the (usually silicon) boule is grown by Czochralski method, giving each wafer an almost uniform initial doping.
[src:semiconductor-materials/doping-semiconductor] Alternately, synthesis of semiconductor devices may involve the use of vapor-phase epitaxy.
[src:semiconductor-materials/doping-semiconductor] In vapor-phase epitaxy, a gas containing the dopant precursor can be introduced into the reactor.
[src:semiconductor-materials/doping-semiconductor] For example, in the case of n-type gas doping of gallium arsenide, hydrogen sulfide is added, and sulfur is incorporated into the structure.
[src:semiconductor-materials/doping-semiconductor] This process is characterized by a constant concentration of sulfur on the surface.
[src:semiconductor-materials/doping-semiconductor] In the case of semiconductors in general, only a very thin layer of the wafer needs to be doped in order to obtain the desired electronic properties.
[src:semiconductor-materials/doping-semiconductor] Thermal diffusion doping, simply known as diffusion, is widely used in silicon photovoltaics and uses chemicals such as Boron tribromide or diborane as a source for doping with boron.
[src:semiconductor-materials/doping-semiconductor] This creates a layer of the dopant on the surface of the wafer and this step is called pre-deposition.
[src:semiconductor-materials/doping-semiconductor] Then a second step, called drive-in, is performed in which the wafer is heated at a higher temperature of 1300 °C to introduce the dopant into the structure of the wafer.
[src:semiconductor-materials/doping-semiconductor] Diffusion can use solid, liquid or gaseous sources with dopant atoms, such as solid boron nitride for boron, arsenic trioxide for arsenic, liquid arsenic trichloride, gaaseous arsine or phosphine.
[src:semiconductor-materials/doping-semiconductor] If using a gaseous source, it is carried to the furnace using a carrier gas such as nitrogen, and then allowed to decompose on the hot surface of the wafer, depositing the desired dopant, such as arsenic for example.
[src:semiconductor-materials/doping-semiconductor] If a liquid source is used, its vapors are carried to the furnace using nitrogen.
[src:semiconductor-materials/doping-semiconductor] The furnace can be either horizontal or vertical.
[src:semiconductor-materials/doping-semiconductor] Spin-on glass or spin-on dopant doping is a two-step process.
[src:semiconductor-materials/doping-semiconductor] First, a mixture of SiO2 and dopants (in a solvent) is applied to a wafer surface by spin-coating.
[src:semiconductor-materials/doping-semiconductor] Then it is stripping and baked at a certain temperature in a furnace with constant nitrogen+oxygen flow.
[src:semiconductor-materials/doping-semiconductor] Neutron transmutation doping (NTD) is an unusual doping method for special applications.
[src:semiconductor-materials/doping-semiconductor] Most commonly, it is used to dope silicon n-type in high-power electronics and semiconductor detectors.
[src:semiconductor-materials/doping-semiconductor] As neutrons continue to pass through the silicon, more and more phosphorus atoms are produced by transmutation, and therefore the doping becomes more and more strongly n-type.
[src:semiconductor-materials/doping-semiconductor] NTD is a far less common doping method than diffusion or ion implantation, but it has the advantage of creating an extremely uniform dopant distribution.
[src:semiconductor-materials/doping-semiconductor] (Note: When discussing periodic table groups, semiconductor physicists always use an older notation, not the current IUPAC group notation.
[src:semiconductor-materials/doping-semiconductor] For the Group IV semiconductors such as diamond, silicon, germanium, silicon carbide, and silicon–germanium, the most common dopants are acceptors from Group III or donors from Group V elements.
[src:semiconductor-materials/doping-semiconductor] Boron, arsenic, phosphorus, and occasionally gallium are used to dope silicon.
[src:semiconductor-materials/doping-semiconductor] Boron is the p-type dopant of choice for silicon integrated circuit production because it diffuses at a rate that makes junction depths easily controllable.
[src:semiconductor-materials/doping-semiconductor] Phosphorus is typically used for bulk-doping of silicon wafers, while arsenic is used to diffuse junctions, because it diffuses more slowly than phosphorus and is thus more controllable.
[src:semiconductor-materials/doping-semiconductor] By doping pure silicon with Group V elements such as phosphorus, extra valence electrons are added that become unbounded from individual atoms and allow the compound to be an electrically conductive n-type semiconductor.
[src:semiconductor-materials/doping-semiconductor] Doping with Group III elements, which are missing the fourth valence electron, creates "broken bonds" (holes) in the silicon lattice that are free to move.
[src:semiconductor-materials/doping-semiconductor] The result is an electrically conductive p-type semiconductor.
[src:semiconductor-materials/doping-semiconductor] In this context, a Group V element is said to behave as an electron **donor**, and a Group III element as an **acceptor**.
[src:semiconductor-materials/doping-semiconductor] This is a key concept in the physics of a diode.
[src:semiconductor-materials/doping-semiconductor] A very heavily doped semiconductor behaves more like a good conductor (metal) and thus exhibits more linear positive thermal coefficient.
[src:semiconductor-materials/doping-semiconductor] Such effect is used for instance in sensistors.
[src:semiconductor-materials/doping-semiconductor] Lower dosage of doping is used in other types (NTC or PTC) thermistors.
[src:semiconductor-materials/doping-semiconductor] In the following list the "(substituting X)" refers to all of the materials preceding said parenthesis.
[src:semiconductor-materials/doping-semiconductor] In most cases many types of impurities will be present in the resultant doped semiconductor.
[src:semiconductor-materials/doping-semiconductor] If an equal number of donors and acceptors are present in the semiconductor, the extra core electrons provided by the former will be used to satisfy the broken bonds due to the latter, so that doping produces no free carriers of either type.
[src:semiconductor-materials/doping-semiconductor] This phenomenon is known as *compensation*, and occurs at the p-n junction in the vast majority of semiconductor devices.
[src:semiconductor-materials/doping-semiconductor] Partial compensation, where donors outnumber acceptors or vice versa, allows device makers to repeatedly reverse (invert) the type of a certain layer under the surface of a bulk semiconductor by diffusing or implanting successively higher doses of dopants, so-called **counterdoping**.
[src:semiconductor-materials/doping-semiconductor] Most modern semiconductor devices are made by successive selective counterdoping steps to create the necessary P and N type areas under the surface of bulk silicon.
[src:semiconductor-materials/doping-semiconductor] This is an alternative to successively growing such layers by epitaxy.
[src:semiconductor-materials/doping-semiconductor] Although compensation can be used to increase or decrease the number of donors or acceptors, the electron and hole mobility is always decreased by compensation because mobility is affected by the sum of the donor and acceptor ions.
[src:semiconductor-materials/doping-semiconductor] Conductive polymers can be doped by adding chemical reactants to oxidize, or sometimes reduce, the system so that electrons are pushed into the conducting orbitals within the already potentially conducting system.
[src:semiconductor-materials/doping-semiconductor] There are two primary methods of doping a conductive polymer, both of which use an oxidation-reduction (i.e., redox) process.
[src:semiconductor-materials/doping-semiconductor] **Electrochemical doping** involves suspending a polymer-coated, working electrode in an electrolyte solution in which the polymer is insoluble along with separate counter and reference electrodes.
[src:semiconductor-materials/doping-semiconductor] An electric potential difference is created between the electrodes that causes a charge and the appropriate counter ion from the electrolyte to enter the polymer in the form of electron addition (i.e., n-doping) or removal (i.e., p-doping).
[src:semiconductor-materials/doping-semiconductor] N-doping is much less common because the Earth's atmosphere is oxygen-rich, thus creating an oxidizing environment.
[src:semiconductor-materials/doping-semiconductor] An electron-rich, n-doped polymer will react immediately with elemental oxygen to *de-dope* (i.e., reoxidize to the neutral state) the polymer.
[src:semiconductor-materials/doping-semiconductor] Thus, chemical n-doping must be performed in an environment of inert gas (e.g., argon).
[src:semiconductor-materials/doping-semiconductor] Electrochemical n-doping is far more common in research, because it is easier to exclude oxygen from a solvent in a sealed flask.
[src:semiconductor-materials/doping-semiconductor] However, it is unlikely that n-doped conductive polymers are available commercially.
[src:semiconductor-materials/doping-semiconductor] Molecular dopants are preferred in doping molecular semiconductors due to their compatibilities of processing with the host, that is, similar evaporation temperatures or controllable solubility.
[src:semiconductor-materials/doping-semiconductor] Additionally, the relatively large sizes of molecular dopants compared with those of metal ion dopants (such as Li+ and Mo6+) are generally beneficial, yielding excellent spatial confinement for use in multilayer structures, such as OLEDs and Organic solar cells.
[src:semiconductor-materials/doping-semiconductor] Typical p-type dopants include F4-TCNQ and Mo(tfd)3.
[src:semiconductor-materials/doping-semiconductor] However, similar to the problem encountered in doping conductive polymers, air-stable n-dopants suitable for materials with low electron affinity (EA) are still elusive.
[src:semiconductor-materials/doping-semiconductor] Recently, photoactivation with a combination of cleavable dimeric dopants, such as [RuCp∗Mes]2, suggests a new path to realize effective n-doping in low-EA materials.
[src:semiconductor-materials/doping-semiconductor] The inclusion of dopant elements to impart dilute magnetism is of growing significance in the field of magnetic semiconductors.
[src:semiconductor-materials/doping-semiconductor] The presence of disperse ferromagnetic species is key to the functionality of emerging spintronics, a class of systems that utilise electron spin in addition to charge.
[src:semiconductor-materials/doping-semiconductor] Using density functional theory (DFT) the temperature dependent magnetic behaviour of dopants within a given lattice can be modeled to identify candidate semiconductor systems.
[src:semiconductor-materials/doping-semiconductor] The sensitive dependence of a semiconductor's properties on dopants has provided an extensive range of tunable phenomena to explore and apply to devices.
[src:semiconductor-materials/doping-semiconductor] It is possible to identify the effects of a solitary dopant on commercial device performance as well as on the fundamental properties of a semiconductor material.
[src:semiconductor-materials/doping-semiconductor] New applications have become available that require the discrete character of a single dopant, such as single-spin devices in the area of quantum information or single-dopant transistors.
[src:semiconductor-materials/doping-semiconductor] Dramatic advances in the past decade towards observing, controllably creating and manipulating single dopants, as well as their application in novel devices have allowed opening the new field of solotronics (solitary dopant optoelectronics).
[src:semiconductor-materials/doping-semiconductor] Electrons or holes introduced by doping are mobile, and can be spatially separated from dopant atoms they have dissociated from.
[src:semiconductor-materials/doping-semiconductor] Ionized donors and acceptors however attract electrons and holes, respectively, so this spatial separation requires abrupt changes of dopant levels, of band gap (e.g. a quantum well), or built-in electric fields (e.g. in case of noncentrosymmetric crystals).
[src:semiconductor-materials/doping-semiconductor] This technique is called modulation doping and is advantageous owing to suppressed carrier-donor scattering, allowing very high mobility to be attained.
[src:semiconductor-materials/gallium-arsenide] Gallium arsenide is used in the manufacture of devices such as microwave frequency integrated circuits, monolithic microwave integrated circuits, infrared light-emitting diodes, laser diodes, solar cells and optical windows.
[src:semiconductor-materials/gallium-arsenide] GaAs is often used as a substrate material for the epitaxial growth of other III-V semiconductors, including indium gallium arsenide, aluminum gallium arsenide and others.
[src:semiconductor-materials/gallium-arsenide] Gallium arsenide was first synthesized and studied by Victor Goldschmidt in 1926 by passing arsenic vapors mixed with hydrogen over gallium(III) oxide at 600 °C.
[src:semiconductor-materials/gallium-arsenide] The semiconductor properties of GaAs and other III-V compounds were patented by Heinrich Welker at Siemens-Schuckert in 1951 and described in a 1952 publication.
[src:semiconductor-materials/gallium-arsenide] Commercial production of its monocrystals commenced in 1954, and more studies followed in the 1950s.
[src:semiconductor-materials/gallium-arsenide] In the compound, gallium has a +3 oxidation state.
[src:semiconductor-materials/gallium-arsenide] Oxidation of GaAs occurs in air, degrading performance of the semiconductor.
[src:semiconductor-materials/gallium-arsenide] The surface can be passivated by depositing a cubic gallium(II) sulfide layer using a tert-butyl gallium sulfide compound such as (t BuGaS) 7.
[src:semiconductor-materials/gallium-arsenide] In the presence of excess arsenic, GaAs boules grow with crystallographic defects; specifically, arsenic antisite defects (an arsenic atom at a gallium atom site within the crystal lattice).
[src:semiconductor-materials/gallium-arsenide] The electronic properties of these defects (interacting with others) cause the Fermi level to be pinned to near the center of the band gap, so that this GaAs crystal has very low concentration of electrons and holes.
[src:semiconductor-materials/gallium-arsenide] This low carrier concentration is similar to an intrinsic (perfectly undoped) crystal, but much easier to achieve in practice.
[src:semiconductor-materials/gallium-arsenide] These crystals are called "semi-insulating", reflecting their high resistivity of 107–109 Ω·cm (which is quite high for a semiconductor, but still much lower than a true insulator like glass).
[src:semiconductor-materials/gallium-arsenide] The HBT can be used in integrated injection logic (I2L).
[src:semiconductor-materials/gallium-arsenide] The earliest GaAs logic gate used Buffered FET Logic (BFL).
[src:semiconductor-materials/gallium-arsenide] Some electronic properties of gallium arsenide are superior to those of silicon.
[src:semiconductor-materials/gallium-arsenide] It has a higher saturated electron velocity and higher electron mobility, allowing gallium arsenide transistors to function at frequencies in excess of 250 GHz.
[src:semiconductor-materials/gallium-arsenide] GaAs devices are relatively insensitive to overheating due to their wider energy band gap.
[src:semiconductor-materials/gallium-arsenide] They also tend to create less noise (disturbance in an electrical signal) in electronic circuits than silicon devices, especially at high frequencies, due to higher carrier mobilities and lower resistive device parasitics.
[src:semiconductor-materials/gallium-arsenide] These superior properties are compelling reasons to use GaAs circuitry in mobile phones, satellite communications, microwave point-to-point links and higher frequency radar systems.
[src:semiconductor-materials/gallium-arsenide] It is also used in the manufacture of Gunn diodes for the generation of microwaves.
[src:semiconductor-materials/gallium-arsenide] Another advantage of GaAs is that it has a direct band gap, which means that it can be used to absorb and emit light efficiently.
[src:semiconductor-materials/gallium-arsenide] Silicon has an indirect band gap and so is relatively poor at emitting light.
[src:semiconductor-materials/gallium-arsenide] As a wide direct band gap material with resulting resistance to radiation damage, GaAs is an excellent material for outer space electronics and optical windows in high power applications.
[src:semiconductor-materials/gallium-arsenide] Because of its wide band gap, pure GaAs is highly resistive.
[src:semiconductor-materials/gallium-arsenide] Combined with a high dielectric constant, this property makes GaAs a very good substrate for integrated circuits and unlike Si provides natural isolation between devices and circuits.
[src:semiconductor-materials/gallium-arsenide] This has made it an ideal material for monolithic microwave integrated circuits (MMICs), where active and essential passive components can readily be produced on a single slice of GaAs.
[src:semiconductor-materials/gallium-arsenide] One of the first GaAs microprocessors was developed in the early 1980s by the RCA Corporation and was considered for the Star Wars program of the United States Department of Defense.
[src:semiconductor-materials/gallium-arsenide] These processors were several times faster and several orders of magnitude more radiation resistant than their silicon counterparts, but were more expensive.
[src:semiconductor-materials/gallium-arsenide] Other GaAs processors were implemented by the supercomputer vendors Cray Computer Corporation, Convex, and Alliant in an attempt to stay ahead of the ever-improving CMOS microprocessor.
[src:semiconductor-materials/gallium-arsenide] Cray eventually built one GaAs-based machine in the early 1990s, the Cray-3, but the effort was not adequately capitalized, and the company filed for bankruptcy in 1995.
[src:semiconductor-materials/gallium-arsenide] Complex layered structures of gallium arsenide in combination with aluminium arsenide (AlAs) or the alloy AlxGa1−xAs can be grown using molecular-beam epitaxy (MBE) or using metalorganic vapor-phase epitaxy (MOVPE).
[src:semiconductor-materials/gallium-arsenide] Because GaAs and AlAs have almost the same lattice constant, the layers have very little induced strain, which allows them to be grown almost arbitrarily thick.
[src:semiconductor-materials/gallium-arsenide] This allows extremely high performance and high electron mobility HEMT transistors and other quantum well devices.
[src:semiconductor-materials/gallium-arsenide] GaAs is used for monolithic radar power amplifiers (but GaN can be less susceptible to heat damage).
[src:semiconductor-materials/gallium-arsenide] Silicon has three major advantages over GaAs for integrated circuit manufacture.
[src:semiconductor-materials/gallium-arsenide] First, silicon is abundant and cheap to process in the form of silicate minerals.
[src:semiconductor-materials/gallium-arsenide] The economies of scale available to the silicon industry has also hindered the adoption of GaAs.
[src:semiconductor-materials/gallium-arsenide] In addition, a Si crystal has a very stable structure and can be grown to very large diameter boules and processed with very good yields.
[src:semiconductor-materials/gallium-arsenide] It is also a fairly good thermal conductor, thus enabling very dense packing of transistors that need to get rid of their heat of operation, all very desirable for design and manufacturing of very large ICs.
[src:semiconductor-materials/gallium-arsenide] Such good mechanical characteristics also make it a suitable material for the rapidly developing field of nanoelectronics.
[src:semiconductor-materials/gallium-arsenide] Naturally, a GaAs surface cannot withstand the high temperatures needed for diffusion; however a viable and actively pursued alternative as of the 1980s was ion implantation.
[src:semiconductor-materials/gallium-arsenide] The second major advantage of Si is the existence of a native oxide (silicon dioxide, SiO2), which is used as an insulator.
[src:semiconductor-materials/gallium-arsenide] Silicon dioxide can be incorporated onto silicon circuits easily, and such layers are adherent to the underlying silicon.
[src:semiconductor-materials/gallium-arsenide] SiO2 is not only a good insulator (with a band gap of 8.9 eV), but the Si-SiO2 interface can be easily engineered to have excellent electrical properties, most importantly low density of interface states.
[src:semiconductor-materials/gallium-arsenide] GaAs does not have a native oxide, does not easily support a stable adherent insulating layer, and does not possess the dielectric strength or surface passivating qualities of the Si-SiO2.
[src:semiconductor-materials/gallium-arsenide] Aluminum oxide (Al2O3) has been extensively studied as a possible gate oxide for GaAs (as well as InGaAs).
[src:semiconductor-materials/gallium-arsenide] The third advantage of silicon is that it possesses a higher hole mobility compared to GaAs (500 versus 400 cm2V−1s−1).
[src:semiconductor-materials/gallium-arsenide] This high mobility allows the fabrication of higher-speed P-channel field-effect transistors, which are required for CMOS logic.
[src:semiconductor-materials/gallium-arsenide] Because they lack a fast CMOS structure, GaAs circuits must use logic styles which have much higher power consumption; this has made GaAs logic circuits unable to compete with silicon logic circuits.
[src:semiconductor-materials/gallium-arsenide] For manufacturing solar cells, silicon has relatively low absorptivity for sunlight, meaning about 100 micrometers of Si is needed to absorb most sunlight.
[src:semiconductor-materials/gallium-arsenide] Such a layer is relatively robust and easy to handle.
[src:semiconductor-materials/gallium-arsenide] In contrast, the absorptivity of GaAs is so high that only a few micrometers of thickness are needed to absorb all of the light.
[src:semiconductor-materials/gallium-arsenide] Consequently, GaAs thin films must be supported on a substrate material.
[src:semiconductor-materials/gallium-arsenide] Silicon is a pure element, avoiding the problems of stoichiometric imbalance and thermal unmixing of GaAs.
[src:semiconductor-materials/gallium-arsenide] Silicon has a nearly perfect lattice; impurity density is very low and allows very small structures to be built (down to 5 nm in commercial production as of 2020).
[src:semiconductor-materials/gallium-arsenide] In contrast, GaAs has a very high impurity density, which makes it difficult to build integrated circuits with small structures, so the 500 nm process is a common process for GaAs.
[src:semiconductor-materials/gallium-arsenide] Silicon has about three times the thermal conductivity of GaAs, with less risk of local overheating in high power devices.
[src:semiconductor-materials/gallium-arsenide] Gallium arsenide (GaAs) transistors are used in the RF power amplifiers for cell phones and wireless communicating.
[src:semiconductor-materials/gallium-arsenide] GaAs wafers are used in laser diodes, photodetectors, and radio frequency (RF) amplifiers for mobile phones and base stations.
[src:semiconductor-materials/gallium-arsenide] GaAs transistors are also integral to monolithic microwave integrated circuits (MMICs), utilized in satellite communication and radar systems, as well as in low-noise amplifiers (LNAs) that enhance weak signals.
[src:semiconductor-materials/gallium-arsenide] Gallium arsenide is an important semiconductor material for high-cost, high-efficiency solar cells and is used for single-crystalline thin-film solar cells and for multi-junction solar cells.
[src:semiconductor-materials/gallium-arsenide] The first known operational use of GaAs solar cells in space was for the Venera 3 mission, launched in 1965.
[src:semiconductor-materials/gallium-arsenide] The GaAs solar cells, manufactured by Kvant, were chosen because of their higher performance in high temperature environments.
[src:semiconductor-materials/gallium-arsenide] GaAs cells were then used for the Lunokhod rovers for the same reason.
[src:semiconductor-materials/gallium-arsenide] In 1970, the GaAs heterostructure solar cells were developed by the team led by Zhores Alferov in the USSR, achieving much higher efficiencies.
[src:semiconductor-materials/gallium-arsenide] In the early 1980s, the efficiency of the best GaAs solar cells surpassed that of conventional, crystalline silicon-based solar cells.
[src:semiconductor-materials/gallium-arsenide] In the 1990s, GaAs solar cells took over from silicon as the cell type most commonly used for photovoltaic arrays for satellite applications.
[src:semiconductor-materials/gallium-arsenide] Later, dual- and triple-junction solar cells based on GaAs with germanium and indium gallium phosphide layers were developed as the basis of a triple-junction solar cell, which held a record efficiency of over 32% and can operate also with light as concentrated as 2,000 suns.
[src:semiconductor-materials/gallium-arsenide] This kind of solar cell powered the Mars Exploration Rovers Spirit and Opportunity, which explored Mars' surface.
[src:semiconductor-materials/gallium-arsenide] Also many solar cars utilize GaAs in solar arrays, as did the Hubble Telescope.
[src:semiconductor-materials/gallium-arsenide] GaAs-based devices hold the world record for the highest-efficiency single-junction solar cell at 29.1% (as of 2019).
[src:semiconductor-materials/gallium-arsenide] This high efficiency is attributed to the extreme high quality GaAs epitaxial growth, surface passivation by the AlGaAs, and the promotion of photon recycling by the thin film design.
[src:semiconductor-materials/gallium-arsenide] Today, multi-junction GaAs cells have the highest efficiencies of existing photovoltaic cells and trajectories show that this is likely to continue to be the case for the foreseeable future.
[src:semiconductor-materials/gallium-arsenide] In 2022, Rocket Lab unveiled a solar cell with 33.3% efficiency based on inverted metamorphic multi-junction (IMM) technology.
[src:semiconductor-materials/gallium-arsenide] In IMM, the lattice-matched (same lattice parameters) materials are grown first, followed by mismatched materials.
[src:semiconductor-materials/gallium-arsenide] The top cell, GaInP, is grown first and lattice matched to the GaAs substrate, followed by a layer of either GaAs or GaInAs with a minimal mismatch, and the last layer has the greatest lattice mismatch.
[src:semiconductor-materials/gallium-arsenide] After growth, the cell is mounted to a secondary handle and the GaAs substrate is removed.
[src:semiconductor-materials/gallium-arsenide] A main advantage of the IMM process is that the inverted growth according to lattice mismatch allows a path to higher cell efficiency.
[src:semiconductor-materials/gallium-arsenide] Complex designs of AlxGa1−xAs-GaAs devices using quantum wells can be sensitive to infrared radiation (QWIP).
[src:semiconductor-materials/gallium-arsenide] GaAs diodes can be used for the detection of X-rays.
[src:semiconductor-materials/gallium-arsenide] Despite GaAs-based photovoltaics being the clear champions of efficiency for solar cells, they have relatively limited use in today's market.
[src:semiconductor-materials/gallium-arsenide] In both world electricity generation and world electricity generating capacity, solar electricity is growing faster than any other source of fuel (wind, hydro, biomass, and so on) for the last decade.
[src:semiconductor-materials/gallium-arsenide] However, GaAs solar cells have not currently been adopted for widespread solar electricity generation.
[src:semiconductor-materials/gallium-arsenide] This is largely due to the cost of GaAs solar cells - in space applications, high performance is required and the corresponding high cost of the existing GaAs technologies is accepted.
[src:semiconductor-materials/gallium-arsenide] For example, GaAs-based photovoltaics show the best resistance to gamma radiation and high temperature fluctuations, which are of great importance for spacecraft.
[src:semiconductor-materials/gallium-arsenide] But in comparison to other solar cells, III-V solar cells are two to three orders of magnitude more expensive than other technologies such as silicon-based solar cells.
[src:semiconductor-materials/gallium-arsenide] The primary sources of this cost are the epitaxial growth costs and the substrate the cell is deposited on.
[src:semiconductor-materials/gallium-arsenide] GaAs solar cells are most commonly fabricated utilizing epitaxial growth techniques such as metal-organic chemical vapor deposition (MOCVD) and hydride vapor phase epitaxy (HVPE).
[src:semiconductor-materials/gallium-arsenide] A significant reduction in costs for these methods would require improvements in tool costs, throughput, material costs, and manufacturing efficiency.
[src:semiconductor-materials/gallium-arsenide] Increasing the deposition rate could reduce costs, but this cost reduction would be limited by the fixed times in other parts of the process such as cooling and heating.
[src:semiconductor-materials/gallium-arsenide] The substrate used to grow these solar cells is usually germanium or gallium arsenide which are notably expensive materials.
[src:semiconductor-materials/gallium-arsenide] One of the main pathways to reduce substrate costs is to reuse the substrate.
[src:semiconductor-materials/gallium-arsenide] An early method proposed to accomplish this is epitaxial lift-off (ELO), but this method is time-consuming, somewhat dangerous (with its use of hydrofluoric acid), and requires multiple post-processing steps.
[src:semiconductor-materials/gallium-arsenide] However, other methods have been proposed that use phosphide-based materials and hydrochloric acid to achieve ELO with surface passivation and minimal post-etching residues and allows for direct reuse of the GaAs substrate.
[src:semiconductor-materials/gallium-arsenide] There is also preliminary evidence that spalling could be used to remove the substrate for reuse.
[src:semiconductor-materials/gallium-arsenide] An alternative path to reduce substrate cost is to use cheaper materials, although materials for this application are not currently commercially available or developed.
[src:semiconductor-materials/gallium-arsenide] Yet another consideration to lower GaAs solar cell costs could be concentrator photovoltaics.
[src:semiconductor-materials/gallium-arsenide] Concentrators use lenses or parabolic mirrors to focus light onto a solar cell, and thus a smaller (and therefore less expensive) GaAs solar cell is needed to achieve the same results.
[src:semiconductor-materials/gallium-arsenide] Concentrator systems have the highest efficiency of existing photovoltaics.
[src:semiconductor-materials/gallium-arsenide] So, technologies such as concentrator photovoltaics and methods in development to lower epitaxial growth and substrate costs could lead to a reduction in the cost of GaAs solar cells and forge a path for use in terrestrial applications.
[src:semiconductor-materials/gallium-arsenide] GaAs has been used to produce near-infrared laser diodes since 1962.
[src:semiconductor-materials/gallium-arsenide] It is often used in alloys with other semiconductor compounds for these applications.
[src:semiconductor-materials/gallium-arsenide] Boron and gallium are group III elements, so boron as an impurity primarily occupies the gallium site.
[src:semiconductor-materials/gallium-arsenide] However, a sufficient number occupy the arsenic site and act as acceptors that efficiently trap ionization event holes from the valence band.
[src:semiconductor-materials/gallium-arsenide] After trapping an ionization event hole from the valence band, the boron acceptors can combine radiatively with delocalized donor electrons to produce photons 0.2 eV below the cryogenic band-gap energy (1.52 eV).
[src:semiconductor-materials/gallium-arsenide] This is an efficient radiative process that produces scintillation photons that are not absorbed by the GaAs crystal.
[src:semiconductor-materials/gallium-arsenide] There is no afterglow, because metastable radiative centers are quickly annihilated by the delocalized electrons.
[src:semiconductor-materials/gallium-arsenide] This is evidenced by the lack of thermally induced luminescence.
[src:semiconductor-materials/gallium-arsenide] *N*-type GaAs has a high refractive index (~3.5) and the narrow-beam absorption coefficient is proportional to the free electron density and typically several per cm.
[src:semiconductor-materials/gallium-arsenide] One would expect that almost all of the scintillation photons should be trapped and absorbed in the crystal, but this is not the case.
[src:semiconductor-materials/gallium-arsenide] This cross section is about 107 times larger than Thomson scattering but comparable to the optical cross section of the conduction electrons in a metal mirror.
[src:semiconductor-materials/gallium-arsenide] *N*-type GaAs(Si,B) is commercially grown as 10 kg crystal ingots and sliced into thin wafers as substrates for electronic circuits.
[src:semiconductor-materials/gallium-arsenide] Boron oxide is used as an encapsulant to prevent the loss of arsenic during crystal growth, but also has the benefit of providing boron acceptors for scintillation.
[src:semiconductor-materials/gallium-arsenide] For this purpose an optical fiber tip of an optical fiber temperature sensor is equipped with a gallium arsenide crystal.
[src:semiconductor-materials/gallium-arsenide] Starting at a light wavelength of 850 nm GaAs becomes optically translucent.
[src:semiconductor-materials/gallium-arsenide] Since the spectral position of the band gap is temperature dependent, it shifts about 0.4 nm/K.
[src:semiconductor-materials/gallium-arsenide] The measurement device contains a light source and a device for the spectral detection of the band gap.
[src:semiconductor-materials/gallium-arsenide] With the changing of the band gap, (0.4 nm/K) an algorithm calculates the temperature (all 250 ms).
[src:semiconductor-materials/gallium-arsenide] GaAs may have applications in spintronics as it can be used instead of platinum in spin-charge converters and may be more tunable.
[src:semiconductor-materials/gallium-arsenide] GaAs has been effectively utilized to fabricate traveling-wave amplifiers.
[src:semiconductor-materials/gallium-arsenide] The environment, health and safety aspects of gallium arsenide sources (such as trimethylgallium and arsine) and industrial hygiene monitoring studies of metalorganic precursors have been reported.
[src:semiconductor-materials/gallium-arsenide] California lists gallium arsenide as a carcinogen, as do IARC and ECA, and it is considered a known carcinogen in animals.
[src:semiconductor-materials/p-n-junction] A **p–n junction** is a combination of two types of semiconductor materials, p-type and n-type, in a single crystal.
[src:semiconductor-materials/p-n-junction] The "n" (negative) side contains freely-moving electrons, while the "p" (positive) side contains freely-moving electron holes.
[src:semiconductor-materials/p-n-junction] Connecting the two materials causes creation of a depletion region near the boundary, as the free electrons fill the available holes, which in turn allows electric current to pass through the junction only in one direction.
[src:semiconductor-materials/p-n-junction] p–n junctions represent the simplest case of a semiconductor electronic device; a p–n junction by itself, when connected on both sides to a circuit, is a diode.
[src:semiconductor-materials/p-n-junction] More complex circuit components can be created by further combinations of p-type and n-type semiconductors; for example, the bipolar junction transistor (BJT) is a semiconductor in the form n–p–n or p–n–p.
[src:semiconductor-materials/p-n-junction] Combinations of such semiconductor devices on a single chip allow for the creation of integrated circuits.
[src:semiconductor-materials/p-n-junction] Solar cells and light-emitting diodes (LEDs) are essentially p–n junctions where the semiconductor materials are chosen, and the component's geometry designed, to maximise the desired effect (light absorption or emission).
[src:semiconductor-materials/p-n-junction] A Schottky junction is a similar case to a p–n junction, where instead of an n-type semiconductor, a metal directly serves the role of the "negative" charge provider.
[src:semiconductor-materials/p-n-junction] The invention of the p–n junction is usually attributed to American physicist Russell Ohl of Bell Laboratories in 1939.
[src:semiconductor-materials/p-n-junction] Two years later (1941), Vadim Lashkaryov reported discovery of p–n junctions in Cu2O and silver sulphide photocells and selenium rectifiers.
[src:semiconductor-materials/p-n-junction] The modern theory of p–n junctions was elucidated by William Shockley in his classic work *Electrons and Holes in Semiconductors* (1950).
[src:semiconductor-materials/p-n-junction] A p-doped semiconductor (that is, one where impurities such as Boron are introduced into its crystal lattice) is relatively conductive.
[src:semiconductor-materials/p-n-junction] The same is true of an n-doped semiconductor, but the junction between them—the boundary where the p-doped and n-doped semiconductor materials meet—can become depleted of charge carriers such as electrons, depending on the relative voltages of the two semiconductor regions.
[src:semiconductor-materials/p-n-junction] By manipulating the flow of charge carriers across this depleted layer, p–n junctions can be used as diodes: circuit elements that allow a flow of electricity in one direction but not in the opposite direction.
[src:semiconductor-materials/p-n-junction] This property makes the p–n junction extremely useful in modern semiconductor electronics.
[src:semiconductor-materials/p-n-junction] Negative charge carriers (electrons) can easily flow through the junction from n to p but not from p to n, and the reverse is true for positive charge carriers (Electron hole).
[src:semiconductor-materials/p-n-junction] When the p–n junction is forward-biased, charge carriers flow freely due to the reduction in energy barriers seen by electrons and holes.
[src:semiconductor-materials/p-n-junction] When the p–n junction is reverse-biased, however, the junction barrier (and therefore resistance) becomes greater and charge flow is minimal.
[src:semiconductor-materials/p-n-junction] In a p–n junction, without an external applied voltage, an equilibrium condition is reached in which a potential difference forms across the junction.
[src:semiconductor-materials/p-n-junction] This potential difference is called *built-in potential* $V_{\rm {bi}}$ .
[src:semiconductor-materials/p-n-junction] At the junction, some of the free electrons in the n-type wander into the p-type due to random thermal migration ("diffusion").
[src:semiconductor-materials/p-n-junction] As they diffuse into the p-type they combine with electron holes, and cancel each other out.
[src:semiconductor-materials/p-n-junction] In a similar way, some of the positive holes in the p-type diffuse into the n-type and combine with free electrons and cancel each other out.
[src:semiconductor-materials/p-n-junction] The positively charged ("donor") dopant atoms in the n-type are part of the crystal, and cannot move.
[src:semiconductor-materials/p-n-junction] Thus, in the n-type, a region near the junction has a fixed amount of positive charge.
[src:semiconductor-materials/p-n-junction] The negatively charged ("acceptor") dopant atoms in the p-type are part of the crystal, and cannot move.
[src:semiconductor-materials/p-n-junction] Thus, in the p-type, a region near the junction becomes negatively charged.
[src:semiconductor-materials/p-n-junction] The result is a region near the junction that acts to repel the mobile charges away from the junction because of the electric field that these charged regions create.
[src:semiconductor-materials/p-n-junction] The region near the p–n interface loses electrical neutrality and most of its mobile carriers, forming the depletion layer (see figure A).
[src:semiconductor-materials/p-n-junction] The electric field created in the space charge then tends to counteract further diffusion, resulting in equilibrium.
[src:semiconductor-materials/p-n-junction] The carrier concentration profile at equilibrium is shown in figure A with blue and red lines.
[src:semiconductor-materials/p-n-junction] Also shown are the two counterbalancing phenomena that establish equilibrium.
[src:semiconductor-materials/p-n-junction] The space charge region is a zone with a net charge provided by the fixed ions (donors or acceptors) that have been left *uncovered* by majority carrier diffusion.
[src:semiconductor-materials/p-n-junction] When equilibrium is reached, the charge density is approximated by the displayed step function.
[src:semiconductor-materials/p-n-junction] In fact, since the y-axis of figure A is log-scale, the region is almost completely depleted of majority carriers (leaving a charge density equal to the net doping level), and the edge between the space charge region and the neutral region is quite sharp (see figure B, Q(x) graph).
[src:semiconductor-materials/p-n-junction] The space charge region has the same magnitude of charge on both sides of the p–n interfaces, thus it extends farther on the less doped side in this example (the n side in figures A and B).
[src:semiconductor-materials/p-n-junction] In forward bias, the p-type is connected with a positive electrical terminal and the n-type is connected with a negative terminal.
[src:semiconductor-materials/p-n-junction] The panels show **energy band diagram**, **electric field**, and **net charge density**.
[src:semiconductor-materials/p-n-junction] The built-in potential of the semiconductor varies, depending on the concentration of doping atoms.
[src:semiconductor-materials/p-n-junction] In this example, both p and n junctions are doped at a 1e15 cm−3 (160 μC/cm3) doping level, leading to built-in potential of ~0.59 volts.
[src:semiconductor-materials/p-n-junction] Reducing depletion width can be inferred from the shrinking movement of carriers across the p–n junction, which as a consequence reduces electrical resistance.
[src:semiconductor-materials/p-n-junction] Electrons that cross the p–n junction into the p-type material (or holes that cross into the n-type material) diffuse into the nearby neutral region.
[src:semiconductor-materials/p-n-junction] The amount of minority diffusion in the near-neutral zones determines the amount of current that can flow through the diode.
[src:semiconductor-materials/p-n-junction] Only majority carriers (electrons in n-type material or holes in p-type) can flow through a semiconductor for a macroscopic length.
[src:semiconductor-materials/p-n-junction] With this in mind, consider the flow of electrons across the junction.
[src:semiconductor-materials/p-n-junction] The forward bias causes a force on the electrons pushing them from the N side toward the P side.
[src:semiconductor-materials/p-n-junction] With forward bias, the depletion region is narrow enough that electrons can cross the junction and *inject* into the p-type material.
[src:semiconductor-materials/p-n-junction] However, they do not continue to flow through the p-type material indefinitely, because it is energetically favorable for them to recombine with holes.
[src:semiconductor-materials/p-n-junction] The average length an electron travels through the p-type material before recombining is called the *diffusion length*, and it is typically on the order of micrometers.
[src:semiconductor-materials/p-n-junction] Although the electrons penetrate only a short distance into the p-type material, the electric current continues uninterrupted, because holes (the majority carriers) begin to flow in the opposite direction.
[src:semiconductor-materials/p-n-junction] The total current (the sum of the electron and hole currents) is constant in space, because any variation would cause charge buildup over time (this is Kirchhoff's current law).
[src:semiconductor-materials/p-n-junction] The flow of holes from the p-type region into the n-type region is exactly analogous to the flow of electrons from N to P (electrons and holes swap roles and the signs of all currents and voltages are reversed).
[src:semiconductor-materials/p-n-junction] The electrons and holes travel in opposite directions, but they also have opposite charges, so the overall current is in the same direction on both sides of the diode, as required.
[src:semiconductor-materials/p-n-junction] The Shockley diode equation models the forward-bias operational characteristics of a p–n junction outside the avalanche (reverse-biased conducting) region.
[src:semiconductor-materials/p-n-junction] Connecting the *p-type* region to the *negative* terminal of the voltage supply and the *n-type* region to the *positive* terminal corresponds to reverse bias.
[src:semiconductor-materials/p-n-junction] If a diode is reverse-biased, the voltage at the cathode is comparatively higher than at the anode.
[src:semiconductor-materials/p-n-junction] Therefore, very little current flows until the diode breaks down.
[src:semiconductor-materials/p-n-junction] The connections are illustrated in the adjacent diagram.
[src:semiconductor-materials/p-n-junction] Because the p-type material is now connected to the negative terminal of the power supply, the 'holes' in the p-type material are pulled away from the junction, leaving behind charged ions and causing the width of the depletion region to increase.
[src:semiconductor-materials/p-n-junction] Likewise, because the n-type region is connected to the positive terminal, the electrons are pulled away from the junction, with similar effect.
[src:semiconductor-materials/p-n-junction] This increases the voltage barrier causing a high resistance to the flow of charge carriers, thus allowing minimal electric current to cross the p–n junction.
[src:semiconductor-materials/p-n-junction] The increase in resistance of the p–n junction results in the junction behaving as an insulator.
[src:semiconductor-materials/p-n-junction] The strength of the depletion zone electric field increases as the reverse-bias voltage increases.
[src:semiconductor-materials/p-n-junction] Once the electric field intensity increases beyond a critical level, the p–n junction depletion zone breaks down and current begins to flow, usually by either the Zener or the avalanche breakdown processes.
[src:semiconductor-materials/p-n-junction] Both of these breakdown processes are non-destructive and are reversible, as long as the amount of current flowing does not reach levels that cause the semiconductor material to overheat and cause thermal damage.
[src:semiconductor-materials/p-n-junction] This effect is used to advantage in Zener diode regulator circuits.
[src:semiconductor-materials/p-n-junction] Zener diodes have a low breakdown voltage.
[src:semiconductor-materials/p-n-junction] A standard value for breakdown voltage is for instance 5.6 V.
[src:semiconductor-materials/p-n-junction] This means that the voltage at the cathode cannot be more than about 5.6 V higher than the voltage at the anode (though there is a slight rise with current), because the diode breaks down, and therefore conducts, if the voltage gets any higher.
[src:semiconductor-materials/p-n-junction] This effect limits the voltage over the diode.
[src:semiconductor-materials/p-n-junction] Another application of reverse biasing is Varactor diodes, where the width of the depletion zone (controlled with the reverse bias voltage) changes the capacitance of the diode.
[src:semiconductor-materials/p-n-junction] For a p–n junction, let $C_{A}(x)$ be the concentration of negatively-charged acceptor atoms and $C_{D}(x)$ be the concentrations of positively-charged donor atoms.
[src:semiconductor-materials/p-n-junction] Let $N_{0}(x)$ and $P_{0}(x)$ be the equilibrium concentrations of electrons and holes respectively.
[src:semiconductor-materials/p-n-junction] where V is the electric potential, $\rho$ is the charge density, $\varepsilon$ is permittivity and q is the magnitude of the electron charge.
[src:semiconductor-materials/p-n-junction] Let $d_{p}$ be the width of the depletion region on the p-side and $d_{n}$ the width of the depletion region on the n-side.
[src:semiconductor-materials/p-n-junction] because the total charge on the p and the n side of the depletion region sums to zero.
[src:semiconductor-materials/p-n-junction] $\Delta V$ can be written as $\Delta V_{0}+\Delta V_{\text{ext}}$ , where we have broken up the voltage difference into the equilibrium plus external components.
[src:semiconductor-materials/p-n-junction] The *Shockley ideal diode equation* characterizes the current across a p–n junction as a function of external voltage and ambient conditions (temperature, choice of semiconductor, etc.).
[src:semiconductor-materials/p-n-junction] To see how it can be derived, we must examine the various reasons for current.
[src:semiconductor-materials/p-n-junction] The convention is that the forward (+) direction be pointed against the diode's built-in potential gradient at equilibrium.
[src:semiconductor-materials/semiconductor] A **semiconductor** is a material with electrical conductivity between that of a conductor and an insulator.
[src:semiconductor-materials/semiconductor] Its conductivity can be modified by adding impurities ("doping") to its crystal structure.
[src:semiconductor-materials/semiconductor] When two regions with different doping levels are present in the same crystal, they form a semiconductor junction.
[src:semiconductor-materials/semiconductor] The term "semiconductors" is sometimes used to refer to semiconductor devices such as microchips and computer processors, which work using the physical properties of semiconductors.
[src:semiconductor-materials/semiconductor] The behavior of charge carriers, which include electrons, ions, and electron holes, at these junctions is the basis of diodes, transistors, and most modern electronics.
[src:semiconductor-materials/semiconductor] Some examples of semiconductors are silicon, germanium, gallium arsenide, and elements near the so-called "metalloid staircase" on the periodic table.
[src:semiconductor-materials/semiconductor] After silicon, gallium arsenide is the second-most common semiconductor and is used in laser diodes, solar cells, microwave-frequency integrated circuits, and others.
[src:semiconductor-materials/semiconductor] Silicon is a critical element for fabricating most electronic circuits.
[src:semiconductor-materials/semiconductor] Semiconductor devices can display a range of different useful properties, such as passing current more easily in one direction than the other, showing variable resistance, and having sensitivity to light or heat.
[src:semiconductor-materials/semiconductor] Because the electrical properties of a semiconductor material can be modified by doping and by the application of electrical fields or light, devices made from semiconductors can be used for amplification, switching, and energy conversion.
[src:semiconductor-materials/semiconductor] The term semiconductor is also used to describe materials used in high capacity, medium- to high-voltage cables as part of their insulation, and these materials are often plastic XLPE (cross-linked polyethylene) with carbon black.
[src:semiconductor-materials/semiconductor] The conductivity of silicon can be increased by adding a small amount (of the order of 1 in 108) of pentavalent (antimony, phosphorus, or arsenic) or trivalent (boron, gallium, indium) atoms.
[src:semiconductor-materials/semiconductor] This process is known as doping, and the resulting semiconductors are known as doped or extrinsic semiconductors.
[src:semiconductor-materials/semiconductor] Apart from doping, the conductivity of a semiconductor can be improved by increasing its temperature.
[src:semiconductor-materials/semiconductor] This is contrary to the behavior of a metal, in which conductivity decreases with an increase in temperature.
[src:semiconductor-materials/semiconductor] The modern understanding of the properties of a semiconductor relies on quantum physics to explain the movement of charge carriers in a crystal lattice.
[src:semiconductor-materials/semiconductor] Doping greatly increases the number of charge carriers within the crystal.
[src:semiconductor-materials/semiconductor] When a semiconductor is doped by Group V elements, they will behave like donors creating free electrons, known as "n-type" doping.
[src:semiconductor-materials/semiconductor] When a semiconductor is doped by Group III elements, they will behave like acceptors creating free holes, known as "p-type" doping.
[src:semiconductor-materials/semiconductor] The semiconductor materials used in electronic devices are doped under precise conditions to control the concentration and regions of p- and n-type dopants.
[src:semiconductor-materials/semiconductor] A single semiconductor device crystal can have many p- and n-type regions; the p–n junctions between these regions are responsible for the useful electronic behavior.
[src:semiconductor-materials/semiconductor] Using a hot-point probe, one can determine quickly whether a semiconductor sample is p- or n-type.
[src:semiconductor-materials/semiconductor] A few of the properties of semiconductor materials were observed throughout the mid-19th and first decades of the 20th century.
[src:semiconductor-materials/semiconductor] The first practical application of semiconductors in electronics was the 1904 development of the cat's-whisker detector, a primitive semiconductor diode used in early radio receivers.
[src:semiconductor-materials/semiconductor] Developments in quantum physics led in turn to the invention of the transistor in 1947 and the integrated circuit in 1958.
[src:semiconductor-materials/semiconductor] Semiconductors in their natural state are poor conductors because a current requires flow of electrons, and semiconductors have their valence bands filled, preventing the entire flow of new electrons.
[src:semiconductor-materials/semiconductor] Several developed techniques allow semiconducting materials to behave like conducting materials, such as doping or gating.
[src:semiconductor-materials/semiconductor] These modifications have two outcomes: **n-type** and **p-type**.
[src:semiconductor-materials/semiconductor] These refer to the excess or shortage of electrons, respectively.
[src:semiconductor-materials/semiconductor] A balanced number of electrons would cause a current to flow throughout the material.
[src:semiconductor-materials/semiconductor] A difference in the electric potential on a semiconducting material would cause it to leave thermal equilibrium and create a non-equilibrium situation.
[src:semiconductor-materials/semiconductor] This introduces electrons and holes to the system, which interact via a process called ambipolar diffusion.
[src:semiconductor-materials/semiconductor] Whenever thermal equilibrium is disturbed in a semiconducting material, the number of holes and electrons changes.
[src:semiconductor-materials/semiconductor] Such disruptions can occur as a result of a temperature difference or photons, which can enter the system and create electrons and holes.
[src:semiconductor-materials/semiconductor] The processes that create or annihilate electrons and holes are called generation and recombination, respectively.
[src:semiconductor-materials/semiconductor] In certain semiconductors, excited electrons can relax by emitting light instead of producing heat.
[src:semiconductor-materials/semiconductor] Controlling the semiconductor composition and electrical current allows for the manipulation of the emitted light's properties.
[src:semiconductor-materials/semiconductor] These semiconductors are used in the construction of light-emitting diodes and fluorescent quantum dots.
[src:semiconductor-materials/semiconductor] Semiconductors with high thermal conductivity can be used for heat dissipation and improving thermal management of electronics.
[src:semiconductor-materials/semiconductor] They play a crucial role in electric vehicles, high-brightness LEDs and power modules, among other applications.
[src:semiconductor-materials/semiconductor] Semiconductors have large thermoelectric power factors making them useful in thermoelectric generators, as well as high thermoelectric figures of merit making them useful in thermoelectric coolers.
[src:semiconductor-materials/semiconductor] The most common semiconducting materials are crystalline solids, but amorphous and liquid semiconductors are also known.
[src:semiconductor-materials/semiconductor] These include hydrogenated amorphous silicon and mixtures of arsenic, selenium, and tellurium in a variety of proportions.
[src:semiconductor-materials/semiconductor] These compounds share with better-known semiconductors the properties of intermediate conductivity and a rapid variation of conductivity with temperature, as well as occasional negative resistance.
[src:semiconductor-materials/semiconductor] Such disordered materials lack the rigid crystalline structure of conventional semiconductors such as silicon.
[src:semiconductor-materials/semiconductor] They are generally used in thin film structures, which do not require material of higher electronic quality, being relatively insensitive to impurities and radiation damage.
[src:semiconductor-materials/semiconductor] Almost all of today's electronic technology involves the use of semiconductors, with the most important aspect being integrated circuits (ICs), which are found in desktop computers, laptops, smartphones, and other electronic devices.
[src:semiconductor-materials/semiconductor] Semiconductors for ICs are mass-produced.
[src:semiconductor-materials/semiconductor] To create an ideal semiconducting material, chemical purity is paramount.
[src:semiconductor-materials/semiconductor] Any small imperfection can have a drastic effect on how the semiconducting material behaves due to the scale at which the materials are used.
[src:semiconductor-materials/semiconductor] A high degree of crystalline perfection is also required, since faults in the crystal structure (such as dislocations, twins, and stacking faults) interfere with the semiconducting properties of the material.
[src:semiconductor-materials/semiconductor] Crystalline faults are a major cause of defective semiconductor devices.
[src:semiconductor-materials/semiconductor] The larger the crystal, the more difficult it is to achieve the necessary perfection.
[src:semiconductor-materials/semiconductor] Current mass production processes use crystal ingots between 100 and 300 mm (3.9 and 11.8 in) in diameter, grown as cylinders and sliced into wafers.
[src:semiconductor-materials/semiconductor] The round shape characteristic of these wafers comes from single-crystal ingots usually produced using the Czochralski method.
[src:semiconductor-materials/semiconductor] Silicon wafers were first introduced in the 1940s.
[src:semiconductor-materials/semiconductor] There is a combination of processes that are used to prepare semiconducting materials for ICs.
[src:semiconductor-materials/semiconductor] One process is called thermal oxidation, which forms silicon dioxide on the surface of the silicon.
[src:semiconductor-materials/semiconductor] This is used as a gate insulator and field oxide.
[src:semiconductor-materials/semiconductor] Other processes are called photomasks and photolithography.
[src:semiconductor-materials/semiconductor] This process is what creates the patterns on the circuit in the integrated circuit.
[src:semiconductor-materials/semiconductor] Ultraviolet light is used along with a photoresist layer to create a chemical change that generates the patterns for the circuit.
[src:semiconductor-materials/semiconductor] The etching is the next process that is required.
[src:semiconductor-materials/semiconductor] The part of the silicon that was not covered by the photoresist layer from the previous step can now be etched.
[src:semiconductor-materials/semiconductor] The main process typically used today is called plasma etching.
[src:semiconductor-materials/semiconductor] Plasma etching usually involves an etch gas pumped in a low-pressure chamber to create plasma.
[src:semiconductor-materials/semiconductor] A common etch gas is chlorofluorocarbon, or more commonly known Freon.
[src:semiconductor-materials/semiconductor] A high radio-frequency voltage between the cathode and anode is what creates the plasma in the chamber.
[src:semiconductor-materials/semiconductor] The silicon wafer is located on the cathode, which causes it to be hit by the positively charged ions that are released from the plasma.
[src:semiconductor-materials/semiconductor] The result is silicon that is etched anisotropically.
[src:semiconductor-materials/semiconductor] This is the process that gives the semiconducting material its desired semiconducting properties.
[src:semiconductor-materials/semiconductor] The process introduces an impure atom to the system, which creates the p–n junction.
[src:semiconductor-materials/semiconductor] To get the impure atoms embedded in the silicon wafer, the wafer is first put in a 1,100 degree Celsius chamber.
[src:semiconductor-materials/semiconductor] The atoms are injected in and eventually diffuse with the silicon.
[src:semiconductor-materials/semiconductor] After the process is completed and the silicon has reached room temperature, the doping process is done and the semiconducting wafer is almost prepared.
[src:semiconductor-materials/semiconductor] Semiconductors are defined by their unique electric conductive behavior, somewhere between that of a conductor and an insulator.
[src:semiconductor-materials/semiconductor] The differences between these materials can be understood in terms of the quantum states for electrons, each of which may contain zero or one electron (by the Pauli exclusion principle).
[src:semiconductor-materials/semiconductor] These states are associated with the electronic band structure of the material.
[src:semiconductor-materials/semiconductor] Electrical conductivity arises due to the presence of electrons in states that are delocalized (extending through the material), however in order to transport electrons a state must be *partially filled*, containing an electron only part of the time.
[src:semiconductor-materials/semiconductor] If the state is always occupied with an electron, then it is inert, blocking the passage of other electrons via that state.
[src:semiconductor-materials/semiconductor] The energies of these quantum states are critical since a state is partially filled only if its energy is near the Fermi level (see Fermi–Dirac statistics).
[src:semiconductor-materials/semiconductor] High conductivity in a material comes from it having many partially filled states and much state delocalization.
[src:semiconductor-materials/semiconductor] Metals are good electrical conductors and have many partially filled states with energies near their Fermi level.
[src:semiconductor-materials/semiconductor] Insulators, by contrast, have few partially filled states, their Fermi levels sit within band gaps with few energy states to occupy.
[src:semiconductor-materials/semiconductor] An (intrinsic) semiconductor has a band gap that is smaller than that of an insulator and at room temperature, significant numbers of electrons can be excited to cross the band gap.
[src:semiconductor-materials/semiconductor] A pure semiconductor, however, is not very useful, as it is neither a very good insulator nor a very good conductor.
[src:semiconductor-materials/semiconductor] However, one important feature of semiconductors (and some insulators, known as *semi-insulators*) is that their conductivity can be increased and controlled by doping with impurities and gating with electric fields.
[src:semiconductor-materials/semiconductor] Doping and gating move either the conduction or valence band much closer to the Fermi level and greatly increase the number of partially filled states.
[src:semiconductor-materials/semiconductor] Some wider-bandgap semiconductor materials are sometimes referred to as **semi-insulators**.
[src:semiconductor-materials/semiconductor] When undoped, these have electrical conductivity nearer to that of electrical insulators, however they can be doped (making them as useful as semiconductors).
[src:semiconductor-materials/semiconductor] Semi-insulators find niche applications in micro-electronics, such as substrates for HEMT.
[src:semiconductor-materials/semiconductor] An example of a common semi-insulator is gallium arsenide.
[src:semiconductor-materials/semiconductor] Some materials, such as titanium dioxide, can even be used as insulating materials for some applications, while being treated as wide-gap semiconductors for other applications.
[src:semiconductor-materials/semiconductor] The partial filling of the states at the bottom of the conduction band can be understood as adding electrons to that band.
[src:semiconductor-materials/semiconductor] The electrons do not stay indefinitely (due to the natural thermal recombination) but they can move around for some time.
[src:semiconductor-materials/semiconductor] The actual concentration of electrons is typically very dilute, and so (unlike in metals) it is possible to think of the electrons in the conduction band of a semiconductor as a sort of classical ideal gas, where the electrons fly around freely without being subject to the Pauli exclusion principle.
[src:semiconductor-materials/semiconductor] In most semiconductors, the conduction bands have a parabolic dispersion relation, and so these electrons respond to forces (electric field, magnetic field, etc.) much as they would in a vacuum, though with a different effective mass.
[src:semiconductor-materials/semiconductor] Because the electrons behave like an ideal gas, one may also think about conduction in very simplistic terms such as the Drude model, and introduce concepts such as electron mobility.
[src:semiconductor-materials/semiconductor] For partial filling at the top of the valence band, it is helpful to introduce the concept of an electron hole.
[src:semiconductor-materials/semiconductor] Although the electrons in the valence band are always moving around, a completely full valence band is inert, not conducting any current.
[src:semiconductor-materials/semiconductor] If an electron is taken out of the valence band, then the trajectory that the electron would normally have taken is now missing its charge.
[src:semiconductor-materials/semiconductor] For the purposes of electric current, this combination of the full valence band, minus the electron, can be converted into a picture of a completely empty band containing a positively charged particle that moves in the same way as the electron.
[src:semiconductor-materials/semiconductor] This particle is called a hole, and the collection of holes in the valence band can again be understood in simple classical terms (as with the electrons in the conduction band).
[src:semiconductor-materials/semiconductor] When ionizing radiation strikes a semiconductor, it may excite an electron out of its energy level and consequently leave a hole.
[src:semiconductor-materials/semiconductor] This process is known as *electron-hole pair generation*.
[src:semiconductor-materials/semiconductor] Electron-hole pairs are constantly generated from thermal energy as well, in the absence of any external energy source.
[src:semiconductor-materials/semiconductor] Electron-hole pairs are also apt to recombine.
[src:semiconductor-materials/semiconductor] Conservation of energy demands that these recombination events, in which an electron loses an amount of energy larger than the band gap, be accompanied by the emission of thermal energy (in the form of phonons) or radiation (in the form of photons).
[src:semiconductor-materials/semiconductor] In some states, the generation and recombination of electron–hole pairs are in equipoise.
[src:semiconductor-materials/semiconductor] The number of electron-hole pairs in the steady state at a given temperature is determined by quantum statistical mechanics.
[src:semiconductor-materials/semiconductor] The precise quantum mechanical mechanisms of generation and recombination are governed by the conservation of energy and conservation of momentum.
[src:semiconductor-materials/semiconductor] The product is a function of the temperature, as the probability of getting enough thermal energy to produce a pair increases with temperature, being approximately exp(−*E*G/*kT*), where *k* is the Boltzmann constant, *T* is the absolute temperature and *E*G is bandgap.
[src:semiconductor-materials/semiconductor] The probability of meeting is increased by carrier traps – impurities or dislocations which can trap an electron or hole and hold it until a pair is completed.
[src:semiconductor-materials/semiconductor] Such carrier traps are sometimes purposely added to reduce the time needed to reach the steady-state.
[src:semiconductor-materials/semiconductor] The conductivity of semiconductors may easily be modified by introducing impurities into their crystal lattice.
[src:semiconductor-materials/semiconductor] The process of adding controlled impurities to a semiconductor is known as **doping**.
[src:semiconductor-materials/semiconductor] The amount of impurity, or dopant, added to an *intrinsic* (pure) semiconductor varies its level of conductivity.
[src:semiconductor-materials/semiconductor] Doped semiconductors are referred to as *extrinsic*.
[src:semiconductor-materials/semiconductor] By adding impurity to the pure semiconductors, the electrical conductivity may be varied by factors of thousands or millions.
[src:semiconductor-materials/semiconductor] A 1 cm3 specimen of a metal or semiconductor has the order of 1022 atoms.
[src:semiconductor-materials/semiconductor] In a metal, every atom donates at least one free electron for conduction, thus 1 cm3 of metal contains on the order of 1022 free electrons, whereas a 1 cm3 sample of pure germanium at 20 °C contains about 4.2×1022 atoms, but only 2.5×1013 free electrons and 2.5×1013 holes.
[src:semiconductor-materials/semiconductor] The addition of 0.001% of arsenic (an impurity) donates an extra 1017 free electrons in the same volume and the electrical conductivity is increased by a factor of 10,000.
[src:semiconductor-materials/semiconductor] The materials chosen as suitable dopants depend on the atomic properties of both the dopant and the material to be doped.
[src:semiconductor-materials/semiconductor] In general, dopants that produce the desired controlled changes are classified as either electron acceptors or donors.
[src:semiconductor-materials/semiconductor] Semiconductors doped with *donor* impurities are called *n-type*, while those doped with *acceptor* impurities are known as *p-type*.
[src:semiconductor-materials/semiconductor] The n and p type designations indicate which charge carrier acts as the material's majority carrier.
[src:semiconductor-materials/semiconductor] The opposite carrier is called the minority carrier, which exists due to thermal excitation at a much lower concentration compared to the majority carrier.
[src:semiconductor-materials/semiconductor] For example, the pure semiconductor silicon has four valence electrons that bond each silicon atom to its neighbors.
[src:semiconductor-materials/semiconductor] In silicon, the most common dopants are group III and group V elements.
[src:semiconductor-materials/semiconductor] Group III elements all contain three valence electrons, causing them to function as acceptors when used to dope silicon.
[src:semiconductor-materials/semiconductor] When an acceptor atom replaces a silicon atom in the crystal, a vacant state (an electron "hole") is created, which can move around the lattice and function as a charge carrier.
[src:semiconductor-materials/semiconductor] Group V elements have five valence electrons, which allows them to act as a donor; substitution of these atoms for silicon creates an extra free electron.
[src:semiconductor-materials/semiconductor] Therefore, a silicon crystal doped with boron creates a p-type semiconductor whereas one doped with phosphorus results in an n-type material.
[src:semiconductor-materials/semiconductor] During manufacture, dopants can be diffused into the semiconductor body by contact with gaseous compounds of the desired element, or ion implantation can be used to accurately position the doped regions.
[src:semiconductor-materials/semiconductor] Some materials, when rapidly cooled to a glassy amorphous state, have semiconducting properties.
[src:semiconductor-materials/semiconductor] These include B, Si, Ge, Se, and Te, and there are multiple theories to explain them.
[src:semiconductor-materials/semiconductor] The history of the understanding of semiconductors begins with experiments on the electrical properties of materials.
[src:semiconductor-materials/semiconductor] The properties of the time-temperature coefficient of resistance, rectification, and light-sensitivity were observed starting in the early 19th century.
[src:semiconductor-materials/semiconductor] Thomas Johann Seebeck was the first to notice that semiconductors exhibit special feature such that experiment concerning an Seebeck effect emerged with much stronger result when applying semiconductors, in 1821.
[src:semiconductor-materials/semiconductor] In 1833, Michael Faraday reported that the resistance of specimens of silver sulfide decreases when they are heated.
[src:semiconductor-materials/semiconductor] This is contrary to the behavior of metallic substances such as copper.
[src:semiconductor-materials/semiconductor] In 1839, Alexandre Edmond Becquerel reported observation of a voltage between a solid and a liquid electrolyte, when struck by light, the photovoltaic effect.
[src:semiconductor-materials/semiconductor] In 1873, Willoughby Smith observed that selenium resistors exhibit decreasing resistance when light falls on them.
[src:semiconductor-materials/semiconductor] In 1874, Karl Ferdinand Braun observed conduction and rectification in metallic sulfides, although this effect had been discovered earlier by Peter Munck af Rosenschöld (sv) writing for the *Annalen der Physik und Chemie* in 1835; Rosenschöld's findings were ignored.
[src:semiconductor-materials/semiconductor] Simon Sze stated that Braun's research was the earliest systematic study of semiconductor devices.
[src:semiconductor-materials/semiconductor] Also in 1874, Arthur Schuster found that a copper oxide layer on wires had rectification properties that ceased when the wires are cleaned.
[src:semiconductor-materials/semiconductor] William Grylls Adams and Richard Evans Day observed the photovoltaic effect in selenium in 1876.
[src:semiconductor-materials/semiconductor] A unified explanation of these phenomena required a theory of solid-state physics, which developed greatly in the first half of the 20th century.
[src:semiconductor-materials/semiconductor] In 1878 Edwin Herbert Hall demonstrated the deflection of flowing charge carriers by an applied magnetic field, the Hall effect.
[src:semiconductor-materials/semiconductor] Thomson in 1897 prompted theories of electron-based conduction in solids.
[src:semiconductor-materials/semiconductor] Karl Baedeker, by observing a Hall effect with the reverse sign to that in metals, theorized that copper iodide had positive charge carriers.
[src:semiconductor-materials/semiconductor] Johan Koenigsberger classified solid materials like metals, insulators, and "variable conductors" in 1914 although his student Josef Weiss already introduced the term ***Halbleiter*** (a semiconductor in modern meaning) in his Ph.D. thesis in 1910.
[src:semiconductor-materials/semiconductor] Felix Bloch published a theory of the movement of electrons through atomic lattices in 1928.
[src:semiconductor-materials/semiconductor] In 1930, Bernhard Gudden stated that conductivity in semiconductors was due to minor concentrations of impurities.
[src:semiconductor-materials/semiconductor] By 1931, the band theory of conduction had been established by Alan Herries Wilson and the concept of band gaps had been developed.
[src:semiconductor-materials/semiconductor] Schottky and Nevill Francis Mott developed models of the potential barrier and of the characteristics of a metal–semiconductor junction.
[src:semiconductor-materials/semiconductor] By 1938, Boris Davydov had developed a theory of the copper-oxide rectifier, identifying the effect of the p–n junction and the importance of minority carriers and surface states.
[src:semiconductor-materials/semiconductor] Agreement between theoretical predictions (based on developing quantum mechanics) and experimental results was sometimes poor.
[src:semiconductor-materials/semiconductor] This was later explained by John Bardeen as due to the extreme "structure sensitive" behavior of semiconductors, whose properties change dramatically based on tiny amounts of impurities.
[src:semiconductor-materials/semiconductor] Commercially pure materials of the 1920s containing varying proportions of trace contaminants produced differing experimental results.
[src:semiconductor-materials/semiconductor] This spurred the development of improved material refining techniques, culminating in modern semiconductor refineries producing materials with parts-per-trillion purity.
[src:semiconductor-materials/semiconductor] Devices using semiconductors were at first constructed based on empirical knowledge before semiconductor theory provided a guide to the construction of more capable and reliable devices.
[src:semiconductor-materials/semiconductor] Alexander Graham Bell used the light-sensitive property of selenium to transmit sound over a beam of light in 1880.
[src:semiconductor-materials/semiconductor] A working solar cell, of low efficiency, was constructed by Charles Fritts in 1883, using a metal plate coated with selenium and a thin layer of gold; the device became commercially useful in photographic light meters in the 1930s.
[src:semiconductor-materials/semiconductor] Point-contact microwave detector rectifiers made of lead sulfide were used by Jagadish Chandra Bose in 1904; the cat's-whisker detector using natural galena or other materials became a common device in the development of radio.
[src:semiconductor-materials/semiconductor] However, it was somewhat unpredictable in operation and required manual adjustment for best performance.
[src:semiconductor-materials/semiconductor] Round observed light emission when electric current passed through silicon carbide crystals, the principle behind the light-emitting diode.
[src:semiconductor-materials/semiconductor] Oleg Losev observed similar light emission in 1922, but at the time the effect had no practical use.
[src:semiconductor-materials/semiconductor] Power rectifiers, using copper oxide and selenium, were developed in the 1920s and became commercially important as an alternative to vacuum tube rectifiers.
[src:semiconductor-materials/semiconductor] The first semiconductor devices used galena, including German physicist Ferdinand Braun's crystal detector in 1874 and Indian physicist Jagadish Chandra Bose's radio crystal detector in 1901.
[src:semiconductor-materials/semiconductor] In the years preceding World War II, infrared detection and communications devices prompted research into lead-sulfide and lead-selenide materials.
[src:semiconductor-materials/semiconductor] These devices were used for detecting ships and aircraft, for infrared rangefinders, and for voice communication systems.
[src:semiconductor-materials/semiconductor] The point-contact crystal detector became vital for microwave radio systems since available vacuum tube devices could not serve as detectors above about 4000 MHz; advanced radar systems relied on the fast response of crystal detectors.
[src:semiconductor-materials/semiconductor] Considerable research and development of silicon materials occurred during the war to develop detectors of consistent quality.
[src:semiconductor-materials/semiconductor] Detector and power rectifiers could not amplify a signal.
[src:semiconductor-materials/semiconductor] Many efforts were made to develop a solid-state amplifier and were successful in developing a device called the point contact transistor which could amplify 20 dB or more.
[src:semiconductor-materials/semiconductor] In 1922, Oleg Losev developed two-terminal, negative resistance amplifiers for radio, but he died in the Siege of Leningrad after successful completion.
[src:semiconductor-materials/semiconductor] In 1926, Julius Edgar Lilienfeld patented a device resembling a field-effect transistor, but it was not practical.
[src:semiconductor-materials/semiconductor] Holden started investigating solid-state amplifiers in 1938.
[src:semiconductor-materials/semiconductor] The first p–n junction in silicon was observed by Russell Ohl about 1941 when a specimen was found to be light-sensitive, with a sharp boundary between p-type impurity at one end and n-type at the other.
[src:semiconductor-materials/semiconductor] A slice cut from the specimen at the p–n boundary developed a voltage when exposed to light.
[src:semiconductor-materials/semiconductor] The first working transistor was a point-contact transistor invented by John Bardeen, Walter Houser Brattain, and William Shockley at Bell Labs in 1947.
[src:semiconductor-materials/semiconductor] Shockley had earlier theorized a field-effect amplifier made from germanium and silicon, but he failed to build such a working device, before eventually using germanium to invent the point-contact transistor.
[src:semiconductor-materials/semiconductor] In France, during the war, Herbert Mataré had observed amplification between adjacent point contacts on a germanium base.
[src:semiconductor-materials/semiconductor] After the war, Mataré's group announced their "Transistron" amplifier only shortly after Bell Labs announced the "transistor".
[src:semiconductor-materials/semiconductor] In 1954, physical chemist Morris Tanenbaum fabricated the first silicon junction transistor at Bell Labs.
[src:semiconductor-materials/semiconductor] However, early junction transistors were relatively bulky devices that were difficult to manufacture on a mass-production basis, which limited them to a number of specialised applications.
